entry.content:
We had a key commitment with a key "id" field that fits in uint32_t, but was rejected by the trust token commitment parser.

Per the spec: 
`
"id" field provides the identifier of the key commitment. It is a non-negative integer that is within the range of an unsigned 32 bit integer type. Values should be montonically increasing.
`

A value of 0x80000000 (2147483648 decimal) fits in an unsigned 32 bit integer, but is not accepted by the parser.

As an example, the following test case fails when added to services/network/trust_tokens/trust_token_key_commitment_parser_unittest.cc:

```
TEST(TrustTokenKeyCommitmentParser, AcceptsKeyWithLargeIdExpiryAndBody) {
  base::test::TaskEnvironment env(
      base::test::TaskEnvironment::TimeSource::MOCK_TIME);

  base::Time one_minute_from_now = base::Time::Now() + base::Minutes(1);
  int64_t one_minute_from_now_in_micros =
      (one_minute_from_now - base::Time::UnixEpoch()).InMicroseconds();

  const std::string input = base::StringPrintf(
      R"({ "PrivateStateTokenV1PMB": {
            "protocol_version": "PrivateStateTokenV1PMB", "id": 2147483648,
            "batchsize": 5,
            "keys": {"1": { "Y": "akey", "expiry": "%s" }}
         }})",
      base::NumberToString(one_minute_from_now_in_micros).c_str());

  // Sanity check that the input is actually valid JSON,
  // and that the given time is valid.
  ASSERT_TRUE(base::JSONReader::Read(input));

  auto my_key = mojom::TrustTokenVerificationKey::New();
  ASSERT_TRUE(base::Base64Decode("akey", &my_key->body));
  my_key->expiry = one_minute_from_now;

  auto result = TrustTokenKeyCommitmentParser().Parse(input);
  ASSERT_TRUE(result);
  EXPECT_THAT(result->keys, ElementsAre(EqualsMojo(my_key)));
}
```
